            Pennsylvania Railroad under J. Edgar Thomson and others, tariff bills, the economic
            cycle of booms and depressions, the evolution of the monetary and banking system,
            telegraph companies, coal mining, Lake Superior copper mining, and Bell's active
            interest in Whig and Republican Party politics. Papers of the Civil War period
            illustrate the impact of the conflict on the business community in the North, and on the
            people of Pennsylvania during Confederate raids and invasions. Some papers relate to
            tests of Pennsylvania iron made at the Washington Navy Yard by Captain Dahlgren, to
            Bell's service as agent of Jay Cooke in floating Federal loans in Pennsylvania, and to
            the effect of the war on the banking system. Included are two early railroad broadsides
            from Bellefontaine and Indiana Railroad and Union Pacific Railroad (1856 and 1867).</p>
